			Used car or Pre-Owned cars. The days are gone where car salesmen are offering you a car that was previously owned by a granny who’s only driving it to church or to the market every Sunday. Nowadays, even the latest model cars are now ups for grab in different <a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=-aHR0cDovL2xpc3Rvbm5ldC5jb20v" target="_blank">;dealerships</a>; . Not only you can get it at a lower price compared to the brand new counterpart, you can also save yourself the depreciation hit of the brand new cars.
<br />;<br />;A brand new car which costs $25,000 will approximately have a $5,000 depreciation value after 5 years of usage by the first owner. A $5,000 is already a big amount of money and can be spend to buy some accessories to your car. So I guess in my opinion that buying a used car is a wise choice.
<br />;<br />;Furthermore, dealerships lately are offering a “<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=-aHR0cDovL2xpc3Rvbm5ldC5jb20vaW5kZXgucGhwP3BfaWQ9NA__" target="_blank">;certified pre-owned car</a>; ” program. A certified pre-owned car means that the used car that they are selling have gone through rigorous inspection and repairing process. Usually the certified pre-owned cars are covered by a warranty from the manufacturers. In this case, buyers of pre-owned cars can relax and can have a peace of mind that their car will still last for years.
<br />;<br />;Don’t get me wrong, used cars doesn’t have that new-car smell of the brand new cars but is it worth it? I mean, the $5,000 which you will save if you buy a used car is the price for the new-car smell? Heck, I’m not paying for it. I can buy lots of car air freshener with my 5 grand. That smell is not important when buying a car. It’s just a smell for God’s sake. Nevertheless, if you’re rich and have tons of dollars at the bank then go ahead and buy yourself a <a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=-aHR0cDovL2xpc3Rvbm5ldC5jb20vaW5kZXgucGhwP3BfaWQ9Mw__" target="_blank">;brand new car</a>; .
